#!/bin/dash
#
# my-appleRAID - The Swiss Army knife for disks and RAIDs on macOS.
#
# POSIX/dash-compatible. Verbose by default: every destructive or
# state-changing command is printed before being executed.
#
# Feature overview:
#   - Disks: list, identify (LED blink), safe-eject, SMART drill-down,
#     wipe / verify-wipe, hot-add replacement.
#   - AppleRAID: list, status, create (mirror/stripe/concat), guided
#     repair of degraded sets, rename, destroy, AutoRebuild policy
#     management, non-destructive test of a set.
#   - SoftRAID interop: migrate a SoftRAID mirror to AppleRAID,
#     release a SoftRAID volume, pre/post-flight uninstall checks.
#   - Unattended health monitoring (`my-appleRAID health`) integrated
#     with launchd. Polls RAID set state every minute (cheap) and runs
#     SMART checks once per day (cheap on power / spin-up wear).
#   - On problems: plays an audible alarm (configurable volume strategy),
#     logs, and sends rate-limited email via msmtp.
#   - State-change aware: only re-alarms/re-emails on configurable intervals
#     so a failed drive doesn't produce 1440 emails per day.
#   - Self-tests: schedulable SMART short/long self-tests via smartctl -t.
#   - Surfaces what macOS hides: AppleRAID-AutoRebuild and
#     AppleRAID-SetTimeout (diskutil does not expose these at all).
#
# Config search path (first readable file wins):
#   $MY_APPLERAID_CONFIG        (env var, for testing)
#   /LINKS/default/my-appleRAID.conf
#   $HOME/.my-appleRAID.conf
#   /usr/local/etc/my-appleRAID.conf
#   /etc/my-appleRAID.conf
#
# See `appleRAID --help` for full command list and `appleRAID create-config
# <path>` to produce a well-commented default config.
